SIMPLE: retard
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Retard
<hw>Re*tard"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Retarded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Retarding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L. <ets>retardare</ets>,
<ets>retardatum</ets>; pref. <ets>re-</ets> re- + <ets>tardare</ets> to
make slow, to delay, fr. <ets>tardus</ets> slow: cf. F.
<ets>retarder</ets>. See <er>Tardy</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To keep
delaying; to continue to hinder; to prevent from progress; to render
more slow in progress; to impede; to hinder; <as>as, to <ex>retard</ex>
the march of an army; to <ex>retard</ex> the motion of a ship</as>; --
opposed to <ant>accelerate</ant>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To put off; to postpone; <as>as, to <ex>retard</ex>
the attacks of old age; to <ex>retard</ex> a rupture between
nations.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To impede; hinder; obstruct; detain; delay;
procrastinate; postpone; defer.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Retard
<hw>Re*tard"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To stay back.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Sir. T. Browne.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retard</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Retard
<hw>Re*tard"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Retardation;
delay.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A mentally retarded person.</def> <mark>[Colloq. and
disparaging]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>a person who is stupid or inept, especially in
social situations.</def> <mark>[Colloq. and disparaging]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Retard of the tide</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Age of the tide</b></col></mcol>, <cd>the interval between the
transit of the moon at which a tide originates and the appearance of the
tide itself. It is found, in general, that any particular tide is not
principally due to the moon's transit immediately proceeding, but to a
transit which has occured some time before, and which is said to
correspond to it. The <xex>retard of the tide</xex> is thus
distinguished from the <xex>lunitidal interval</xex>. See under
<er>Retardation</er>.</cd> <au>Ham. Nav. Encyc.</au></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Retardation</ent>⟦br⟧
